And at New York's Clinton Prison:

Some have stated that sudden withdrawal of the drug is dangerous and cruel. I have never seen a patient die of such procedure and I believe that the memory of their misery has deterred a great many addicts from resuming the habit when released (Kossef 1925).

Toward the close of the 1920s, as growing numbers of heroin addicts were being sentenced to federal penitentiaries, several members of Congress advocated the establishment of federal "narcotics farms" for the treatment of drug-addicted prisoners. The result was the Porter Narcotic Farm Act in 1929, which led to the establishment of narcotics farms (later called Public Health Service hospitals) at Lexington, Kentucky in 1935 and at Fort Worth, Texas in 1938 (Trebach 1982; Eddy 1973). Under the Porter Act, drug. offenders convicted in federal courts could be sent to the "narco farms" by the sentencing judge in lieu of conventional imprisonment. This became the principal function of Lexington and Fort Worth, which were, in fact, run like medium security prisons (King 1972). The six-month treatment regimen included detoxification, psychotherapy, and vocational counseling, and, although follow-up studies found the programs to be generally ineffective (Brecher 1972), they represented the first attempt at comprehensive prison-based drug treatment.
Prison treatment programs in the 1950s and 1960s, although still few in number, had begun to reflect the innovations in rehabilitative approaches that were appearing in the wider community - group therapy (Rosenthal and
Shimberg 1958; Dwyer 1971), methadone detoxification (Dole 1972), methadone maintenance (Dole et al. 1969), and therapeutic communities (Inciardi and Scarpitti 1992).
Throughout the 1960s and into the 1970s, therapeutic communities, or TCs, were the most visible type of treatment in correctional settings. The first TC was established in 1962 in the Nevada State Prison as an extension of Charles Dederich's Synanon program (Time, 1 March 1963). Several more appeared during the latter half of the decade. In 1967, the Federal Bureau of Prisons established its first TC in its Danbury, Connecticut institution (petersen 1974). As part of Governor Nelson A. Rockefeller's Narcotic Addiction Control Commission and its ill-fated civil commitment program for heroin addicts (Inciardi 1988), a small TC program was piloted in New York's Green Haven Prison, a maximum security facility some ninety miles north of Manhattan. At about the same time, the New York City Addiction Services Agency organized TC
units patterned after Phoenix House at Rikers Island and Hart Island
penitentiaries. From the early 1970s through the early 1980s, prison-based TCs seemed to
come and go - in Arkansas, Connecticut, Georgia, Michigan, Nebraska, New York, Oklahoma, South Carolina, Virginia, the federal system, and elsewhere (Smith 1977; Toch 1980; Weppner 1983). Along with the prison TCs established in the 1960s, almost all were closed, the result of prison crowding, state budget deficits, staff burnout or blowup, and changes in prison leadership. In a few

