Currently, of the estimated 400,000 to 500,000 narcotics users in the United States, combined with the even greater numbers of cocaine, crack, and other illicit drug users, significant numbers come to the attention of criminal justice agencies. Federal efforts in the early 1980s turned toward controlling the supply of drugs, determinate sentencing for drug offenders, and long prison terms. These efforts, not coincidentally, were followed by rapid expansion of the incarcerated population. Bureau of Justice Statistics studies have documented that over 500/0 of federal inmates and 8()OAl of state inmates had been druginvolved before incarceration (Bureau of Justice Statistics 1980; Innes 1988). The Drug Use Forecasting system has estimated that about 7()% of arrestees in major cities test positive for drugs; this finding has been remarkably consistent from 1987 to 1992 (Center for Substance Abuse Research 1992).
With the nation's current "war on drugs" that began about a decade ago, interest in treatment in criminal justice settings has increased. Faced with the burgeoning economic and social costs of drug-related crime and drug-involved criminal justice clients, criminal justice interest in treatment alternatives was raised anew in the mid-1980s. Current interest in treatment in the criminal justice system got its major impetus from the 1986 Anti-Drug Abuse Act, and the subsequent efforts of a variety of federal agencies (including the Bureau of Justice Assistance, the Office of Treatment Improvement, the Bureau of Prisons, the National Institute on Drug Abuse, the U.S. Probation Office, and the National Institute of Corrections) to initiate and encourage treatment options. These practices have also in many cases filtered down to the state level.
Sometimes as a corollary and sometimes as an alternative to prison-based treatment, a movement toward drug treatment in community-based correctional settings emerged in the early 1970s. These programs developed as part of the widespread interest in criminal justice diversion projects, and with the movement away from mandatory sentences, have enjoyed renewed interest in the late 1980s.
The most visible and enduring of these programs was (and remains) the Treatment Alternatives to Street Crime (TASC) program. Under TASC, community-based supervision is made available to drug-involved individuals who would otherwise burden the justice system with their persistent drugassociated criminality. More specifically, TASC identifies, assesses, and refers drug-involved offenders to community treatment services as an alternative or supplement to existing justice system sanctions and procedures. In the more than one hundred jurisdictions where TASC currently operates, it serves as a court diversion mechanism or a supplement to probation supervision. After referral to community-based treatment, TASC monitors the client's progress and compliance, including expectations for abstinence, employment, and improved personal and social functioning. It then reports treatment results back to the referring justice system agency. Clients who violate the conditions of their justice mandate (diversion, deferred sentencing, pretrial intervention, or probation), their TASC contract, or their treatment agreement are typically returned to the justice system for continued processing or sanctions (Inciardi and McBride 1991).

